1
00:00:01,863 --> 00:00:05,799
I told Hilly I wasn't ready to go out on
any date. Wasn't even close to ready.

2
00:00:10,304 --> 00:00:12,795
I was engaged last year. She ended it.

3
00:00:12,907 --> 00:00:14,272
I'm sure she did.

4
00:00:14,442 --> 00:00:16,876
It's not like that.
I'm not always a jerk.

5
00:00:19,347 --> 00:00:22,714
We had been dating since we were 15,
and you know how it is.

6
00:00:22,850 --> 00:00:25,876
Actually, I don't. I've never really
dated anyone before.

7
00:00:26,487 --> 00:00:27,511
Ever?

8
00:00:28,556 --> 00:00:29,580
Ever.

9
00:00:31,559 --> 00:00:33,959
All right, I, uh...

10
00:00:35,863 --> 00:00:37,353
Well, that must be it, then.

11
00:00:37,498 --> 00:00:38,863
- What?
- You, Skeeter.

12
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:41,434
I've never met a woman that says
exactly what she's thinking.

13
00:00:41,569 --> 00:00:44,402
- Well, I got plenty to say.
- Yeah, I'll bet you do.

14
00:00:46,240 --> 00:00:48,401
You make me laugh, smile.

15
00:00:52,179 --> 00:00:53,908
Would you like to come
have dinner with me?

16
00:00:55,483 --> 00:00:58,850
We could talk. I could actually
listen to you this time.

17
00:00:59,754 --> 00:01:01,722
I can't think of anything worse.

18
00:01:03,491 --> 00:01:05,288
I understand, and I'm sorry.

19
00:01:05,426 --> 00:01:07,986
That's what
I came here to say, and I said it.

20
00:01:15,303 --> 00:01:16,429
Just give me a minute.

21
00:01:17,371 --> 00:01:18,633
Let me get my sweater.

22
00:01:24,779 --> 00:01:26,474
Not a big fan of oysters, huh?

23
00:01:26,614 --> 00:01:29,344
Oysters are a vehicle
for crackers and ketchup.

24
00:01:31,052 --> 00:01:33,452
Well, here's to new beginnings.

25
00:01:39,126 --> 00:01:40,616
Mm.

26
00:01:42,730 --> 00:01:43,822
You're disgusting.

27
00:01:43,965 --> 00:01:45,592
You've already made that pretty clear.

28
00:01:46,601 --> 00:01:49,297
And just so you know,
the boys caught me reading

29
00:01:49,437 --> 00:01:51,428
your <i>Miss Myrna</i> column
on the rig the other day.

30
00:01:51,572 --> 00:01:54,097
Really? You read them?

31
00:01:54,241 --> 00:01:55,265
All of them.

32
00:01:56,210 --> 00:01:57,609
Very informative, too.

33
00:01:57,745 --> 00:02:00,578
I had no idea that ground egg shells
got grease out of clothes.

34
00:02:00,681 --> 00:02:02,148
Well, I do my homework.

35
00:02:08,222 --> 00:02:09,917
You're a good writer, Skeeter.

36
00:02:11,359 --> 00:02:12,383
Thank you.

37
00:02:15,096 --> 00:02:16,723
I want to be a journalist.

38
00:02:17,798 --> 00:02:20,961
Or maybe a novelist. Or maybe both.

39
00:02:21,636 --> 00:02:23,069
I like that.

40
00:02:25,373 --> 00:02:27,739
You're really smart. And pretty.

41
00:02:36,684 --> 00:02:37,981
Skeeter.

42
00:02:39,286 --> 00:02:41,151
I hope you get to write something
really good.

43
00:02:42,323 --> 00:02:43,688
Something you believe in.

44
00:02:56,070 --> 00:02:57,094
Hello?

45
00:02:59,340 --> 00:03:02,434
What? I'm coming!

46
00:03:02,610 --> 00:03:06,011
Aibileen! Come on. We have to go
help Hilly. Right now!

47
00:03:10,618 --> 00:03:14,110
Oh! You're trespassing!

48
00:03:14,288 --> 00:03:16,222
It's Skeeter!

49
00:03:16,357 --> 00:03:17,722
She put it in the newsletter.

50
00:03:17,858 --> 00:03:19,086
Oh, my God.

51
00:03:19,226 --> 00:03:23,890
I specifically said,
"Drop old coats at my house."

52
00:03:24,031 --> 00:03:26,090
Not commodes!

53
00:03:26,233 --> 00:03:28,098
Why would she do this to me?

54
00:03:28,235 --> 00:03:30,100
I don't know. I don't know, Hilly.

55
00:03:30,237 --> 00:03:32,933
It's so embarrassing.

56
00:03:40,981 --> 00:03:42,710
Oh, Lord.

57
00:03:42,850 --> 00:03:44,249
I go potty, Mommy.

58
00:03:45,219 --> 00:03:47,278
No! Mae Mobley!

59
00:03:47,421 --> 00:03:49,480
You get off of that toilet!

60
00:03:51,125 --> 00:03:53,457
- You will catch diseases, you hear me?
- Mommy!

61
00:03:53,594 --> 00:03:55,619
You will catch diseases
on those toilets.

62
00:04:09,376 --> 00:04:13,472
You is kind, you is smart,

63
00:04:13,614 --> 00:04:15,844
you is important.

64
00:04:26,293 --> 00:04:29,285
<i>Don't shop for anything</i>
<i>on Capitol Street.</i>

65
00:04:29,430 --> 00:04:34,333
<i>Let's let the merchants down on</i>
<i>Capitol Street feel the economic pinch.</i>

66
00:04:34,468 --> 00:04:36,436
<i>Let me say this to you.</i>

67
00:04:36,570 --> 00:04:39,300
<i>I had one merchant to call me,</i>
<i>and he said,</i>

68
00:04:39,440 --> 00:04:44,104
<i>"I want you to know that I've</i>
<i>talked to my national office today,</i>

69
00:04:44,245 --> 00:04:47,544
<i>and they want me to tell you that we</i>
<i>don't need nigger business."</i>

70
00:04:48,949 --> 00:04:52,749
<i>These are stores that help to support</i>
<i>the White Citizens' Council,</i>

71
00:04:52,853 --> 00:04:57,119
<i>the council that is dedicated to keeping</i>
<i>you and I second-class citizens.</i>

72
00:04:57,625 --> 00:04:59,115
Mama!

73
00:05:01,929 --> 00:05:03,487
Don't encourage them like that.

74
00:05:03,631 --> 00:05:06,031
- That is national news.
- I won't have it!

75
00:05:08,936 --> 00:05:10,233
You understand?

76
00:05:20,648 --> 00:05:22,013
How you doing, Miss Clark?

77
00:05:23,617 --> 00:05:26,211
All right, Henry.

78
00:05:26,353 --> 00:05:28,253
Thank you. How you doing?

79
00:05:29,557 --> 00:05:33,357
If God is willing, Miss Clark.
If God is willing.

80
00:05:33,494 --> 00:05:34,927
That's good.

81
00:05:35,095 --> 00:05:36,756
- Yeah.
- That's good.

82
00:05:45,372 --> 00:05:46,805
What's going on out there, mister?

83
00:05:46,907 --> 00:05:48,898
Coloured people off.

84
00:05:49,043 --> 00:05:50,670
The rest of you,
let me know where you're going.

85
00:05:50,811 --> 00:05:51,937
I'll get you close as I can.

86
00:05:52,112 --> 00:05:53,704
What happened?

87
00:05:53,848 --> 00:05:55,679
I don't know. Some nigger got shot.

88
00:05:56,650 --> 00:05:58,618
- Where you headed?
- Woodrow Wilson.

89
00:05:58,786 --> 00:06:00,754
Woodrow Wilson. All right.

90
00:06:09,864 --> 00:06:13,698
- You gonna be all right, Miss Clark?
- I'll be all right. You go on now.

91
00:06:13,834 --> 00:06:16,098
- You want me to walk you?
- No, thank you. I'll be all right.

92
00:06:17,404 --> 00:06:18,769
You have a good night.

93
00:06:19,406 --> 00:06:21,169
Which way you going?

94
00:06:29,149 --> 00:06:32,118
<i>We view this as a cold,</i>

95
00:06:32,253 --> 00:06:34,244
<i>brutal, deliberate...</i>

96
00:06:35,389 --> 00:06:39,655
<i>...killing in a savage,</i>
<i>uncivilised state.</i>

97
00:06:39,827 --> 00:06:44,992
<i>There is no state with a record that</i>
<i>approaches that of Mississippi</i>

98
00:06:45,165 --> 00:06:49,329
<i>in inhumanity, murder, brutality</i>

99
00:06:49,503 --> 00:06:51,562
<i>and racial hatred.</i>

100
00:06:51,705 --> 00:06:55,402
<i>It is absolutely at the bottom</i>
<i>of the list.</i>

101
00:06:56,877 --> 00:06:58,003
<i>Fifteen minutes past midnight,</i>

102
00:06:58,178 --> 00:07:01,944
<i>Evers got out of his car beside his home</i>
<i>in a Negro residential area.</i>

103
00:07:02,082 --> 00:07:04,016
<i>In a vacant lot about 40 yards away,</i>

104
00:07:04,184 --> 00:07:07,620
<i>a sniper fired a single shot from a</i>
<i>high-powered rifle at Evers' silhouette.</i>

105
00:07:07,755 --> 00:07:10,121
I'm all right. Sit down. You all right?

106
00:07:10,257 --> 00:07:11,884
- I'm OK.
- <i>The bullet hit him in the back,</i>

107
00:07:11,992 --> 00:07:14,927
<i>crashed through his body,</i>
<i>through a window, into the house.</i>

108
00:07:15,062 --> 00:07:17,553
<i>He died within an hour</i>
<i>at a Jackson hospital.</i>

109
00:07:17,665 --> 00:07:20,031
<i>City detectives believe the fatal shot</i>
<i>was fired from...</i>

110
00:07:20,200 --> 00:07:24,227
KKK shot him. An hour ago.

111
00:07:25,940 --> 00:07:27,931
Right in front of his children,
Aibileen.

112
00:07:29,476 --> 00:07:32,570
We're gonna pray for the Evers.
We're gonna pray for Myrlie.

113
00:07:32,680 --> 00:07:36,116
We living in hell. Trapped.

114
00:07:36,984 --> 00:07:38,451
Our kids, trapped.

115
00:07:41,889 --> 00:07:44,380
Sugar, take your brothers and sisters
and y'all go on to bed.

116
00:07:49,830 --> 00:07:51,695
Good night.

117
00:07:51,832 --> 00:07:54,198
Good night. Good night.

118
00:07:56,570 --> 00:07:58,731
Oh. Good night, baby.

119
00:08:10,317 --> 00:08:12,478
What they gonna do if they catch us
with Miss Skeeter?

120
00:08:13,454 --> 00:08:14,853
We're gonna be careful.

121
00:08:16,123 --> 00:08:20,856
Hitch us to a pickup? Drag us behind?
Shoot me in front of my children?

122
00:08:20,995 --> 00:08:23,520
We ain't doing civil rights.

123
00:08:23,664 --> 00:08:26,633
We're just telling stories
like they really happened.

124
00:08:28,469 --> 00:08:30,835
You're a fool, old woman.

125
00:08:32,006 --> 00:08:33,439
A fool.

126
00:09:04,004 --> 00:09:08,998
Miss Phelan, the presses are heating up.
We needed <i>Miss Myrna</i> 30 minutes ago.

127
00:09:09,576 --> 00:09:10,600
Yes, sir.

128
00:09:10,744 --> 00:09:12,336
Chop-chop.

129
00:09:13,580 --> 00:09:15,013
Good Lord.

130
00:09:30,898 --> 00:09:32,695
Miss Celia?

131
00:09:50,417 --> 00:09:51,475
Miss Celia?

132
00:09:51,618 --> 00:09:53,643
Go home.
I'll see you tomorrow.

133
00:09:53,787 --> 00:09:56,085
You mess up your hair colouring again?

134
00:09:56,223 --> 00:09:59,715
I helped you fix it last time.
We got it back to butter batch.

135
00:09:59,827 --> 00:10:01,454
Was real pretty, remember?

136
00:10:05,466 --> 00:10:06,831
Miss Celia.

137
00:10:07,935 --> 00:10:09,800
I told you, go home!

138
00:10:25,752 --> 00:10:27,310
I said get out!

139
00:10:43,170 --> 00:10:45,764
Why is there so much blood?

140
00:10:51,311 --> 00:10:55,247
Next one's gonna catch, Miss Celia.
You just wait and see.

141
00:10:57,551 --> 00:11:00,247
We got married 'cause I was pregnant.

142
00:11:02,656 --> 00:11:05,022
Then I lost it a month later.

143
00:11:07,528 --> 00:11:09,519
Johnny wants kids now.

144
00:11:13,033 --> 00:11:14,830
What's he gonna do with me?

145
00:11:17,838 --> 00:11:19,135
Well...

146
00:11:20,507 --> 00:11:22,532
Mr Johnny just gonna have
to get over it.

147
00:11:25,045 --> 00:11:27,138
He doesn't know about the baby.

148
00:11:31,318 --> 00:11:33,218
Or the two before.

149
00:12:28,075 --> 00:12:29,440
Yule Mae Davis?

150
00:12:32,312 --> 00:12:34,644
- What do you want me to do?
- You're under arrest.

151
00:12:35,849 --> 00:12:39,216
Just call my husband.
Just call my husband.

152
00:12:42,889 --> 00:12:46,222
- Wait a minute. I want my purse.
- No, you're under arrest.

153
00:12:46,326 --> 00:12:50,160
I want to get my purse.
I want to get my purse! Aibee!

154
00:12:50,931 --> 00:12:53,126
- Don't fight, Yule Mae!
- Aibee!

155
00:12:53,267 --> 00:12:57,363
Aibee, I want my purse! I want my purse!

156
00:13:01,275 --> 00:13:03,243
Just let me go!

157
00:13:03,977 --> 00:13:06,275
Yule Mae, don't fight.

158
00:13:14,788 --> 00:13:17,951
I knew she was a thief
the day she started.

159
00:13:18,759 --> 00:13:22,957
A nigra walks into a pawn shop
with a ring of such size and colour.

160
00:13:24,264 --> 00:13:27,358
It took them all of ten minutes
to find out where she worked.

161
00:13:29,369 --> 00:13:31,701
I am desperate for
a grilled cheese sandwich.

162
00:13:31,838 --> 00:13:34,306
Are you? Are you?
Do you want a grilled cheese sandwich?

163
00:13:34,441 --> 00:13:36,204
Oh, yes.

164
00:13:36,343 --> 00:13:38,038
Just go sit down over there.

165
00:13:44,685 --> 00:13:49,088
Miss Skeeter, you best head on over
to Miss Aibileen's house.

166
00:13:49,856 --> 00:13:50,880
Now.

167
00:14:21,355 --> 00:14:23,550
I'm gonna help with your stories.

168
00:14:24,891 --> 00:14:27,257
I'm gonna help, too. Mm-hm.

169
00:14:29,096 --> 00:14:30,324
We all are.

170
00:14:30,430 --> 00:14:33,422
- That's right.
- I'll help you.

171
00:14:34,768 --> 00:14:37,259
I used to take
a shortcut every day

172
00:14:37,404 --> 00:14:40,134
when I went to work
at Dr Dixon's house.

173
00:14:40,774 --> 00:14:43,868
Cut through that farmer's lower 40
to get there.

174
00:14:44,010 --> 00:14:47,878
One day this farmer
was waiting for me with a gun.

175
00:14:48,014 --> 00:14:51,609
Said he'd shoot me dead
if I walked on his land again.

176
00:14:52,319 --> 00:14:58,053
Dr Dixon went and paid that farmer
double for two of those acres.

177
00:14:58,558 --> 00:15:01,425
Told him he was gonna
start farming, too.

178
00:15:02,362 --> 00:15:07,061
But he bought that just for me,
so I could get to work easy.

179
00:15:08,335 --> 00:15:09,563
He did.

180
00:15:09,703 --> 00:15:12,763
I worked for Miss Jolene's mother
till the day she died.

181
00:15:13,607 --> 00:15:17,134
Then her daughter, Miss Nancy,
asked me to come and work for her.

182
00:15:18,211 --> 00:15:20,509
Miss Nancy is a real sweet lady.

183
00:15:21,481 --> 00:15:25,918
But Miss Jolene's ma done put it in her
will I got to work for Miss Jolene.

184
00:15:26,920 --> 00:15:29,787
Miss Jolene's a mean woman.

185
00:15:29,923 --> 00:15:31,481
Mean for sport.

186
00:15:33,794 --> 00:15:36,558
Lord, I tried to find another job.

187
00:15:37,564 --> 00:15:39,725
But in everybody's mind

188
00:15:39,833 --> 00:15:43,269
the French family
and Miss Jolene owned me.

189
00:15:45,405 --> 00:15:46,770
Owned me.

190
00:15:52,479 --> 00:15:54,310
<i>I leave early</i>
<i>this week for Thanksgiving.</i>

191
00:15:54,448 --> 00:15:57,281
Our last editors' meeting
is December 17th,

192
00:15:57,417 --> 00:15:59,180
so if you want a prayer
of this getting read,

193
00:15:59,319 --> 00:16:02,345
- <i>I'd better have it by then.</i>
- That's in three weeks, Miss Stein.

194
00:16:02,489 --> 00:16:05,014
Well, otherwise it goes in the pile.

195
00:16:05,158 --> 00:16:07,991
You do not want it in the pile.

196
00:16:08,128 --> 00:16:09,220
Yes, ma'am.

197
00:16:09,396 --> 00:16:12,763
And put something personal in there.
Write about the maid who raised you.

198
00:16:14,100 --> 00:16:15,465
I understand.

199
00:16:23,109 --> 00:16:25,907
Well, we have a lot of work to do
before the benefit, don't we?

200
00:16:26,079 --> 00:16:29,105
I know, but I think we're on track.
We're doing quite well.

201
00:16:37,424 --> 00:16:38,914
- It's so good.
- Mm-hm.

202
00:16:39,092 --> 00:16:40,923
- Who's there?
- I don't know.

203
00:16:41,695 --> 00:16:42,719
Aibileen?

204
00:16:45,198 --> 00:16:46,825
Hey, Elizabeth!

205
00:16:46,967 --> 00:16:49,333
It's me, Celia Foote.

206
00:16:51,438 --> 00:16:54,896
I was in the neighbourhood.
Thought I'd drop by.

207
00:16:56,543 --> 00:16:59,273
Everybody hide.
Everybody get down, get down.

208
00:17:00,180 --> 00:17:02,478
Get down! Get down! Get down!

209
00:17:05,652 --> 00:17:07,586
- Turn off the music.
- Who are we hiding from?

210
00:17:07,721 --> 00:17:09,586
Shh!

211
00:17:12,893 --> 00:17:15,691
Hey!

212
00:17:15,829 --> 00:17:16,887
Shh!

213
00:17:20,800 --> 00:17:22,165
I brought a chocolate pie!

214
00:17:24,471 --> 00:17:26,735
My maid, Minny, made it.

215
00:17:34,047 --> 00:17:36,379
She's in the bushes.

216
00:17:58,104 --> 00:18:02,905
Don't be taking those women
any more pies, you understand?

217
00:18:11,184 --> 00:18:14,620
They made me stand there like I was
the vacuum salesman.

218
00:18:16,656 --> 00:18:17,884
Why, Minny?

219
00:18:19,960 --> 00:18:23,896
Because they know about you getting
knocked up by Mr Johnny.

220
00:18:23,997 --> 00:18:25,965
Mad you married one of their mens.

221
00:18:26,766 --> 00:18:30,702
And especially since Miss Hilly and
Mr Johnny had just broke up, too.

222
00:18:30,870 --> 00:18:33,430
Hilly probably thinks that I was
fooling around with Johnny

223
00:18:33,573 --> 00:18:35,268
when they were still going steady.

224
00:18:35,408 --> 00:18:37,501
Mm-hm.

225
00:18:37,644 --> 00:18:41,944
And Missus Walters always said Miss
Hilly still sweet on Mr Johnny, too.

226
00:18:43,783 --> 00:18:45,307
No wonder!

227
00:18:48,288 --> 00:18:52,486
They don't hate me.
They hate what they think I did.

228
00:18:53,326 --> 00:18:56,022
They hate you 'cause they think
you white trash.

229
00:18:56,162 --> 00:18:59,131
I'm just going to have to tell Hilly
I ain't no boyfriend stealer.

230
00:19:00,700 --> 00:19:03,533
In fact, I'll tell her Friday night
at the benefit.

231
00:19:04,638 --> 00:19:06,970
You don't need to be going
to that benefit, Miss Celia.

232
00:19:09,109 --> 00:19:11,703
Did you hear me? You just stay home.

233
00:19:15,815 --> 00:19:17,009
That looks bad.

234
00:19:19,352 --> 00:19:20,717
Let me take a look.

235
00:19:21,588 --> 00:19:23,283
I got to get these peas on.

236
00:19:23,390 --> 00:19:26,188
I know you didn't fall
in no tub, Minny.

237
00:19:47,414 --> 00:19:50,008
You know what I'd do if I were you?

238
00:19:51,718 --> 00:19:53,845
I'd give it right back to him.

239
00:19:55,355 --> 00:19:58,256
I'd hit him over the head
with a skillet,

240
00:19:58,391 --> 00:20:01,189
and I'd tell him, "Go straight to hell."

241
00:20:11,571 --> 00:20:13,937
<i>From here, the members of the family...</i>

242
00:20:17,310 --> 00:20:20,677
<i>...visitors from foreign countries</i>
<i>and others</i>

243
00:20:20,780 --> 00:20:23,806
<i>will walk to St. Matthew's Cathedral.</i>

244
